1
00:00:02,960 --> 00:00:06,280
SAM GARNER: "New York,
the city of a million stories.

2
00:00:07,480 --> 00:00:10,080
"Half of them are true, the other half

3
00:00:11,120 --> 00:00:13,160
"Just haven't happened yet.

4
00:00:17,240 --> 00:00:19,080
"Statues, the man said."”

5
00:00:19,160 --> 00:00:20,840
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

6
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:24,240
"Living statues that moved in the dark.”

7
00:00:33,400 --> 00:00:36,400
MAN: So, will you take the case,
Mr Garner?

8
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:39,040
Sure. Why not?

9
00:00:39,680 --> 00:00:41,320
Because you don't believe me.

10
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:45,440
For $25 a day plus expenses,
I'll believe any damn thing you like.

11
00:00:45,720 --> 00:00:48,080
But you don't believe
that statues can move.

12
00:00:50,920 --> 00:00:54,200
(CHUCKLES) And you're right, Mr Garner.
They can't.

13
00:00:54,640 --> 00:00:56,600
Of course they can't...

14
00:01:00,600 --> 00:01:02,080
...when you're looking.

15
00:01:04,680 --> 00:01:06,520
Good night, Mr Grayle.

16
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:41,280
GARNER: "The address Grayle gave me was
an apartment block near Battery Park.

17
00:01:41,360 --> 00:01:44,000
"He said it was where the statues lived.

18
00:01:44,480 --> 00:01:47,280
"I asked him
why he didn't go look himself.

19
00:01:48,120 --> 00:01:49,760
"He didn't answer.

20
00:01:50,520 --> 00:01:53,000
"Grayle was the scariest guy I knew.

21
00:01:53,720 --> 00:01:55,680
"If something scared him,

22
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:58,680
"I kind of wanted to shake its hand."

23
00:02:39,360 --> 00:02:40,400
(DOOR CLOSES)

24
00:02:40,480 --> 00:02:41,640
Hello?

25
00:02:43,240 --> 00:02:44,400
Hello?

26
00:02:52,920 --> 00:02:54,720
(LIFT BELL DINGS)

27
00:03:04,520 --> 00:03:05,800
What the...

28
00:03:11,600 --> 00:03:13,400
(LIFT BELL DINGS)

29
00:03:21,720 --> 00:03:23,320
(FLOOR CREAKING)

30
00:03:44,640 --> 00:03:45,680
(KNOCKS)

31
00:03:45,760 --> 00:03:48,600
Hello? Anyone home?

32
00:04:09,080 --> 00:04:10,880
(MAN GRUNTING SOFTLY)

33
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:13,560
Hello?

34
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:19,840
(KNOCKS)

35
00:04:22,480 --> 00:04:23,560
Who are you?

36
00:04:25,480 --> 00:04:28,720
They're coming for you.
They're going to send you back.

37
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:31,000
Who's coming? Back where?

38
00:04:31,080 --> 00:04:34,400
In time. Back in time.

39
00:04:35,240 --> 00:04:36,480
I'm you.

40
00:04:40,160 --> 00:04:42,000
I'm you.

41
00:04:51,800 --> 00:04:53,600
(LIFT BELL DINGS)

42
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:16,560
(CRASHING STEPS)

43
00:05:30,600 --> 00:05:32,320
You got to be kidding me.

44
00:05:33,720 --> 00:05:35,400
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

45
00:06:23,240 --> 00:06:25,280
DOCTOR: “New York growls at my window,

46
00:06:26,360 --> 00:06:27,880
"but I was ready for it.

47
00:06:28,600 --> 00:06:32,360
"My stocking seams were straight,
my lipstick was combat-ready,

48
00:06:32,440 --> 00:06:36,520
"and I was packing cleavage
that could fell an ox at 20 feet..."

49
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:38,120
Doctor, you're doing it again.

50
00:06:38,200 --> 00:06:41,160
-I'm reading!
-Aloud. Please, could you not?

51
00:06:44,840 --> 00:06:46,960
There's something different about you,
isn't there?

52
00:06:47,040 --> 00:06:49,040
-What's the book?
-Melody Malone.

53
00:06:49,120 --> 00:06:52,120
She's a private detective
in old town New York.

54
00:06:52,200 --> 00:06:54,480
She's got ice in her heart
and a kiss on her lips

55
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:57,440
and a vulnerable side
she keeps well-hidden.

56
00:06:58,760 --> 00:06:59,800
Oh, you've read it?

57
00:06:59,880 --> 00:07:02,440
You read it, aloud,
and then went, "Yowzah!"

58
00:07:02,520 --> 00:07:05,080
You know, only you
could fancy someone in a book.

59
00:07:05,160 --> 00:07:06,720
I'm just reading. I just like the cover.

60
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:08,720
Ooh! Can we see the cover?

61
00:07:08,800 --> 00:07:10,480
No. No, I'm busy.

62
00:07:11,480 --> 00:07:13,520
It's your hair. Is it your hair?

63
00:07:13,600 --> 00:07:15,600
Oh, shut up. It's the glasses.

64
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:19,360
I wear reading glasses now, on my nose.
See? There you go.

65
00:07:19,480 --> 00:07:21,800
I don't like them.
They make your eyes look all liney.

66
00:07:22,840 --> 00:07:26,600
No, actually. Sorry. They're fine.
Carry on.

67
00:07:26,840 --> 00:07:29,480
Okay. I'm going to go and get us
some more coffee. Who wants more coffee?

68
00:07:29,560 --> 00:07:31,520
-Me, too. I'll go.
-Rory?

69
00:07:32,760 --> 00:07:34,800
Do I have
noticeable lines on my eyes now?

70
00:07:34,880 --> 00:07:36,160
-Yes.
-No.

71
00:07:37,120 --> 00:07:38,120
You didn't look.

72
00:07:38,640 --> 00:07:40,400
I noticed them earlier...
Didn't notice them.

73
00:07:40,480 --> 00:07:43,720
I specifically remember
not noticing them.

74
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:45,600
You're welcome on the firepit,
Centurion.

75
00:07:46,080 --> 00:07:47,720
Do I have to come over there?

76
00:07:48,120 --> 00:07:49,320
You can if you like.

77
00:07:49,400 --> 00:07:53,640
-Well, we have company.
-I'll get a babysitter.

78
00:07:53,720 --> 00:07:55,080
(DOCTOR SIGHS)

79
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:58,320
Do you know, it is so humiliating
when you do that.

80
00:07:59,800 --> 00:08:01,400
-Coffee?
-Coffee.

81
00:08:03,440 --> 00:08:05,040
Can I have a go?

82
00:08:06,600 --> 00:08:07,640
Oh.

83
00:08:09,080 --> 00:08:10,840
Actually, that is much better.

84
00:08:11,120 --> 00:08:12,760
That is exciting.

85
00:08:13,840 --> 00:08:14,840
Read to me.

86
00:08:14,920 --> 00:08:16,960
I thought you didn't like
my reading aloud.

87
00:08:17,040 --> 00:08:19,480
Shut up and read me a story.
Just don't go, "Yowzah!"

88
00:08:22,720 --> 00:08:23,760
Why did you do that?

89
00:08:23,840 --> 00:08:27,520
I always rip out the last page
of a book, then it doesn't have to end.

90
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:29,200
I hate endings.

91
00:08:31,720 --> 00:08:35,120
"As I crossed the street,
I saw the thin guy.

92
00:08:35,800 --> 00:08:37,040
"But he didn't see me.

93
00:08:38,400 --> 00:08:40,600
"I guess that's how it began."”

94
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:56,760
(DISTORTED, SQUEAKY LAUGHTER)

95
00:09:06,840 --> 00:09:08,840
(DISTORTED, SQUEAKY LAUGHTER)

96
00:09:15,760 --> 00:09:17,840
(LAUGHTER CONTINUES)

97
00:09:22,080 --> 00:09:25,760
"I followed the skinny guy
for two more blocks before he turned

98
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:28,440
"and I could ask
exactly what he was doing here.

99
00:09:28,520 --> 00:09:29,560
"He looked a little scared,

100
00:09:29,640 --> 00:09:32,800
"so I gave him my best smile
and my bluest eyes."

101
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:37,040
Beware the yowzah.
Do not, at this point, yowz.

102
00:09:40,920 --> 00:09:43,440
Doctor? What did the skinny guy say?

103
00:09:44,920 --> 00:09:48,520
He said, "I just went to get coffees
for the Doctor and Amy.

104
00:09:48,960 --> 00:09:50,200
"Hello, River."

105
00:09:52,960 --> 00:09:54,480
RIVER: Hello, Dad.

106
00:09:54,560 --> 00:09:57,920
Where am I?
(WHISPERS) How the hell did I get here?

107
00:09:58,320 --> 00:10:00,480
I haven't the faintest idea.

108
00:10:01,240 --> 00:10:03,320
But you'll probably
want to put your hands up.

109
00:10:09,800 --> 00:10:11,080
Melody Malone?

110
00:10:11,160 --> 00:10:12,200
You're Melody!

111
00:10:15,080 --> 00:10:16,160
Get in.

112
00:10:16,440 --> 00:10:19,480
What's River doing in a book?
What's Rory doing in a book?

113
00:10:19,560 --> 00:10:21,200
He went to get coffee. Pay attention.

114
00:10:21,280 --> 00:10:23,480
He went to get coffee and turned up
in a book. How does that work?

115
00:10:23,560 --> 00:10:25,880
I don't know. We're in New York.

116
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:28,720
What is going on?

117
00:10:30,840 --> 00:10:31,880
Where did you get this book?

118
00:10:31,960 --> 00:10:33,720
-It was in my jacket.
-How did it get there?

119
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:35,280
How does anything get there?
I've given up asking.

120
00:10:35,360 --> 00:10:38,200
Date, date. Does she mention a date?
When is this happening?

121
00:10:38,280 --> 00:10:39,720
Yes. Hang on. Uh...

122
00:10:39,880 --> 00:10:41,880
Ooh! April 3rd, 1938.

123
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:44,520
(SIREN WAILING)

124
00:10:45,880 --> 00:10:48,160
You didn't come here
in the Tardis, obviously.

125
00:10:48,400 --> 00:10:51,280
-Why?
-You couldn't have.

126
00:10:51,360 --> 00:10:54,040
Couldn't have?
What does she mean, "couldn't have"?

127
00:10:54,360 --> 00:10:58,960
This city's full of time-distortions,
be impossible to land the Tardis here,

128
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:02,240
like trying to land a plane
in a blizzard.

129
00:11:02,840 --> 00:11:04,200
Even I couldn't do it.

130
00:11:04,560 --> 00:11:05,680
Even who couldn't do it?

131
00:11:05,760 --> 00:11:08,320
Don't you two fall out.
She's only in a book.

132
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:11,960
(CHUCKLES) 1938. Easy one.

133
00:11:24,280 --> 00:11:25,680
(ALARM BLARING)

134
00:11:25,760 --> 00:11:26,880
What was that?

135
00:11:27,360 --> 00:11:30,120
1938. We just bounced off it.

136
00:11:30,200 --> 00:11:31,240
(ALARM STOPS)

137
00:11:32,080 --> 00:11:33,200
RORY: Well, how did you get here?

138
00:11:33,280 --> 00:11:36,920
Vortex manipulator.
Less bulky than a Tardis.

139
00:11:37,520 --> 00:11:39,680
A motorbike through traffic.

140
00:11:40,840 --> 00:11:41,920
You?

141
00:11:42,680 --> 00:11:45,240
I'm...not sure.

142
00:11:55,400 --> 00:11:56,840
AMY: The Weeping Angels.

143
00:11:56,920 --> 00:11:58,560
DOCTOR: That makes sense.
AMY: Makes what?

144
00:11:58,640 --> 00:12:00,800
DOCTOR: That's what happened to Rory.
That's what the Angels do.

145
00:12:00,880 --> 00:12:02,360
It's their preferred form of attack.

146
00:12:02,440 --> 00:12:04,800
They zap you back in time,
let you live to death.

147
00:12:04,880 --> 00:12:07,120
Well, we've got a time machine.
We can just go and get him.

148
00:12:07,240 --> 00:12:08,880
Well, tried that, if you've noticed,

149
00:12:08,960 --> 00:12:12,120
and we are back where we started
in 2012.

150
00:12:12,200 --> 00:12:13,960
We didn't start in a graveyard.
What are we doing here?

151
00:12:14,040 --> 00:12:17,600
Don't know. Probably causally linked,
somehow. Doesn't matter.

152
00:12:17,680 --> 00:12:19,280
Extractor fans on!

153
00:12:19,440 --> 00:12:21,760
Well, we're going to get there somehow.
We're in the rest of the book.

154
00:12:21,840 --> 00:12:22,840
I'm what?

155
00:12:22,920 --> 00:12:24,680
Page 43,
you're going to break something.

156
00:12:25,160 --> 00:12:26,200
I'm what?

157
00:12:26,360 --> 00:12:28,080
"Why do you have to break mine?"
I asked the Doctor.

158
00:12:28,520 --> 00:12:31,280
He frowned and said, "Because Amy read
it in a book and now I have no choice."

159
00:12:31,400 --> 00:12:35,240
Stop! No, no. Stop!
You can't... You can't read ahead.

160
00:12:36,520 --> 00:12:39,960
-You mustn't, and-and you can't do that.
-But we've already been reading it.

161
00:12:40,040 --> 00:12:42,360
Just the stuff that's happening now,
in parallel with us.

162
00:12:42,440 --> 00:12:44,720
-That's as far as we go.
-It could help us find Rory.

163
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:46,720
And if you read ahead
and find that Rory dies?

164
00:12:47,880 --> 00:12:50,640
This isn't any old future, Amy,
it's ours.

165
00:12:51,080 --> 00:12:53,080
Once we know what's coming, it's fixed.

166
00:12:53,160 --> 00:12:56,800
I'm going to break something because
you told me that I'm going to do it.

167
00:12:56,880 --> 00:12:59,080
-No choice now.
-Time can be rewritten.

168
00:13:00,240 --> 00:13:01,280
Not once you've read it.

169
00:13:03,120 --> 00:13:05,680
Once we know what's coming,
it's written in stone.

170
00:13:15,160 --> 00:13:17,920
RIVER: Well, early Chin Dynasty,
I'd say.

171
00:13:18,120 --> 00:13:19,720
GRAYLE: Correct.

172
00:13:20,040 --> 00:13:22,880
Are you an archaeologist
as well as a detective?

173
00:13:25,520 --> 00:13:28,440
Okay. Landing a plane
in a tiny-winy blizzard.

174
00:13:28,520 --> 00:13:30,920
I could push through,
but if I'm out by a nanosecond,

175
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:32,760
the engines will phase
and I'll shatter the planet.

176
00:13:34,400 --> 00:13:36,040
-I need landing lights.
-Landing lights?

177
00:13:36,120 --> 00:13:39,600
Yes. I need a signal to lock on to.
What did she say? Early what dynasty?

178
00:13:39,840 --> 00:13:42,000
Early Chin, just as you say.

179
00:13:43,280 --> 00:13:44,720
You're very well-informed.

180
00:13:44,800 --> 00:13:46,240
And you're very afraid.

181
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:49,120
That's an awful lot of locks
for one door.

182
00:13:54,320 --> 00:13:55,680
RORY: River, I'm translating.

183
00:13:55,760 --> 00:13:57,880
RIVER: It's a gift of the Tardis,
it hangs around.

184
00:13:57,960 --> 00:14:00,760
This one,
put him somewhere uncomfortable.

185
00:14:01,040 --> 00:14:03,480
-Oh, great.
-With the babies, sir?

186
00:14:03,560 --> 00:14:05,000
Yes. Why not?

187
00:14:05,320 --> 00:14:07,480
Give him to the babies.

188
00:14:07,560 --> 00:14:08,560
Ah-ah-ah!

189
00:14:15,960 --> 00:14:17,400
(RORY GROANS)

190
00:14:18,040 --> 00:14:20,000
The lights are out.
You'll last longer with these.

191
00:14:23,880 --> 00:14:24,960
What do you care?

192
00:14:25,080 --> 00:14:26,920
(SCOFFS) It's funnier.

193
00:14:31,120 --> 00:14:32,160
(DOOR LOCKING)

194
00:14:32,240 --> 00:14:33,800
(SQUEAKY GIGGLING)

195
00:14:33,880 --> 00:14:35,280
RORY: Hello?

196
00:14:37,600 --> 00:14:39,720
(WHOOSHING)

197
00:14:43,520 --> 00:14:45,480
Ah. Hello. Yes.

198
00:14:46,800 --> 00:14:48,000
(EXCLAIMS SOFTLY)

199
00:14:48,560 --> 00:14:50,160
Special permission from the Emperor.

200
00:14:54,560 --> 00:14:56,400
Hello, sweetie!

201
00:14:57,160 --> 00:15:01,720
Let's see.
Crime boss with a collecting fetish.

202
00:15:03,880 --> 00:15:06,960
Whatever you don't want anyone else
to see has got to be your favourite,

203
00:15:08,480 --> 00:15:11,400
or possibly your girlfriend.

204
00:15:17,080 --> 00:15:18,960
So, girlfriend, then.

205
00:15:21,080 --> 00:15:22,720
-(DEVICE BLEEPING)
-What are you doing?

206
00:15:22,800 --> 00:15:25,280
Oh, you know, texting a boy.

207
00:15:29,320 --> 00:15:30,600
(BEEPING)

208
00:15:33,120 --> 00:15:34,640
Landing lights.

209
00:15:35,520 --> 00:15:36,960
We have a signal. Locking on.

210
00:15:37,160 --> 00:15:38,480
(GRUNTING)

211
00:15:41,760 --> 00:15:45,000
GRAYLE: These things are all over
and people don't seem to notice.

212
00:15:46,080 --> 00:15:48,400
It never moves while you're looking.

213
00:15:48,480 --> 00:15:51,880
-Oh, I know how they work.
-So I understand.

214
00:15:52,480 --> 00:15:56,560
Melody Malone,
the detective that investigates Angels.

215
00:15:58,440 --> 00:16:02,760
-Badly damaged.
-I wanted to know if it could feel pain.

216
00:16:02,920 --> 00:16:06,040
You realise it's screaming?
The others can hear.

217
00:16:08,120 --> 00:16:10,600
Is that why you need all the locks?

218
00:16:13,240 --> 00:16:14,440
(GASPS)

219
00:16:15,920 --> 00:16:17,880
GRAYLE: You're going to tell me
all about these creatures.

220
00:16:20,040 --> 00:16:22,160
And you're going to do it quickly.

221
00:16:22,720 --> 00:16:23,720
(RIVER GASPS)

222
00:16:26,600 --> 00:16:28,000
(SHUDDERING)

223
00:16:29,520 --> 00:16:30,720
(FOOTSTEPS PATTERING)

224
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:32,400
(HIGH-PITCHED GIGGLING)

225
00:16:37,640 --> 00:16:39,720
RORY: Hello, is someone there?

226
00:16:53,480 --> 00:16:54,720
(WINCES)

227
00:16:54,840 --> 00:16:56,640
(FOOTSTEPS PATTERING)

228
00:17:03,120 --> 00:17:04,920
(FOOTSTEPS PATTERING)

229
00:17:07,880 --> 00:17:09,480
(GIGGLING CONTINUES)

230
00:17:17,280 --> 00:17:19,480
Come on. Oh, come on!

231
00:17:26,960 --> 00:17:29,280
The Angels are predators.
They're deadly.

232
00:17:29,360 --> 00:17:30,480
What do you want with them?

233
00:17:30,920 --> 00:17:34,640
I'm a collector.
What collector could resist these?

234
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:36,520
I'm only human.

235
00:17:37,240 --> 00:17:39,200
That's exactly what they're thinking.

236
00:17:39,280 --> 00:17:40,320
(ELECTRICITY BUZZING)

237
00:17:40,400 --> 00:17:42,640
What's that? What's happening?

238
00:17:43,160 --> 00:17:44,560
Is it an earthquake?

239
00:17:51,440 --> 00:17:52,720
What is it?

240
00:17:54,600 --> 00:17:57,280
RIVER: Oh, you bad boy.
You could burn New York.

241
00:17:59,520 --> 00:18:01,080
What does that mean?

242
00:18:01,160 --> 00:18:05,560
It means, Mr Grayle,
just you wait till my husband gets home.

243
00:18:07,400 --> 00:18:08,680
(GRAYLE SCREAMS)

244
00:18:11,840 --> 00:18:12,840
Come on!

245
00:18:12,920 --> 00:18:15,080
Just a moment. Final checks.

246
00:18:15,440 --> 00:18:16,560
Since when?

247
00:18:31,440 --> 00:18:32,560
Rory?

248
00:18:34,320 --> 00:18:35,440
Rory?

249
00:18:38,720 --> 00:18:39,840
Rory?

250
00:18:40,120 --> 00:18:43,520
Sorry I'm late, honey.
Traffic was hell.

251
00:18:43,960 --> 00:18:45,120
(CHUCKLES)

252
00:18:50,640 --> 00:18:51,800
Shock.

253
00:18:53,840 --> 00:18:56,280
-He'll be fine.
-Not if I can get loose.

254
00:19:02,680 --> 00:19:06,320
So where are you now, Dr Song?
How's prison?

255
00:19:06,680 --> 00:19:10,440
Oh, I was pardoned ages ago.
And it's Professor Song to you.

256
00:19:11,960 --> 00:19:13,640
-Pardoned?
-Mmm.

257
00:19:14,040 --> 00:19:17,360
Turns out the person I killed
never existed in the first place.

258
00:19:17,440 --> 00:19:19,280
Apparently there's no record of him.

259
00:19:19,560 --> 00:19:22,600
It's almost as if
someone's gone around deleting himself

260
00:19:22,680 --> 00:19:28,080
-from every database in the universe.
-Mmm, you said I'd got too big.

261
00:19:28,160 --> 00:19:31,360
And now no one's ever heard of you.
Didn't you used to be somebody?

262
00:19:31,480 --> 00:19:33,680
Well, aren't you the woman
who killed the Doctor?

263
00:19:33,880 --> 00:19:35,520
-Doctor who?
-Ha.

264
00:19:37,320 --> 00:19:38,760
She's holding you very tight.

265
00:19:39,200 --> 00:19:40,760
At least she didn't
send me back in time.

266
00:19:40,840 --> 00:19:41,960
I doubt she's strong enough.

267
00:19:42,040 --> 00:19:45,160
Well, I need a hand back.
So which is it going to be?

268
00:19:45,280 --> 00:19:47,960
Are you going to break my wrist or hers?

269
00:19:49,960 --> 00:19:53,680
Oh, no. Really?
Why do you have to break mine?

270
00:19:53,760 --> 00:19:55,840
Because Amy read it in a book.

271
00:19:55,920 --> 00:19:57,960
And now I have no choice.

272
00:20:01,120 --> 00:20:03,400
-You see?
-Well, what book?

273
00:20:04,160 --> 00:20:05,200
Your book.

274
00:20:05,280 --> 00:20:08,520
Which you haven't written yet,
so we can't read.

275
00:20:08,920 --> 00:20:10,960
I see. I don't like the cover much.

276
00:20:11,040 --> 00:20:13,920
But if River's going to write that book,
she'd make it useful, yeah?

277
00:20:14,040 --> 00:20:15,080
Well, I'll certainly try.

278
00:20:15,160 --> 00:20:16,520
But we can't read ahead,
it's too dangerous.

279
00:20:16,600 --> 00:20:18,440
I know, but there must be something
we can look at.

280
00:20:18,520 --> 00:20:21,920
What, a page of handy hints,
previews, spoiler-free?

281
00:20:23,840 --> 00:20:25,120
Chapter titles.

282
00:20:27,560 --> 00:20:28,600
Hmm?

283
00:20:33,920 --> 00:20:35,360
-He's in the cellar.
-Give me.

284
00:20:43,880 --> 00:20:45,080
Doctor?

285
00:20:45,560 --> 00:20:47,920
Doctor, what is it?
What's wrong? Tell me.

286
00:20:48,960 --> 00:20:52,120
Doctor? Doctor, what is it? Tell me.

287
00:20:56,600 --> 00:20:59,480
Okay. I know that face. Calm down.

288
00:20:59,640 --> 00:21:01,960
-(GRUNTING) No!
-Calm down! Talk to me!

289
00:21:02,040 --> 00:21:03,120
-Doctor?
-No!

290
00:21:03,600 --> 00:21:04,840
You get your wrist out.

291
00:21:04,920 --> 00:21:07,440
You get your wrist out
without breaking it.

292
00:21:08,720 --> 00:21:10,600
-How?
-I don't know. Just do it!

293
00:21:10,680 --> 00:21:12,360
Change the future!

294
00:21:21,560 --> 00:21:22,680
Rory?

295
00:21:25,720 --> 00:21:28,000
-No! They're Angels.
- (EXCLAIMS)

296
00:21:29,120 --> 00:21:30,880
DOCTOR: Baby Angels.

297
00:21:31,400 --> 00:21:34,600
Did they get Rory?
Where is he? Did they take him?

298
00:21:35,720 --> 00:21:37,520
Yes, I think so. Yes.

299
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:40,680
(BABIES GIGGLING, FOOTSTEPS PATTERING)

300
00:21:56,320 --> 00:21:57,880
So, is this what's going to happen?

301
00:21:58,160 --> 00:22:01,080
We just keep chasing him back in time
and they keep pulling him further back?

302
00:22:01,160 --> 00:22:02,360
-(DEVICE CHIMES)
-He isn't back in time.

303
00:22:02,440 --> 00:22:05,240
I'm reading a displacement
but there are no temporal markers.

304
00:22:05,480 --> 00:22:08,000
He's been moved in space
but not in time

305
00:22:08,080 --> 00:22:11,160
and it's not that far from here,
by the look of it.

306
00:22:12,760 --> 00:22:14,120
You got out.

307
00:22:14,840 --> 00:22:16,440
So, where is he?

308
00:22:19,040 --> 00:22:20,720
(DOOR CREAKS OPEN)

309
00:22:23,480 --> 00:22:25,520
(PASSING VEHICLE HONKING)

310
00:22:32,760 --> 00:22:33,800
(DEVICE BLEEPING)

311
00:22:33,880 --> 00:22:35,280
Come on, come on, come on. Where is he?

312
00:22:35,360 --> 00:22:37,240
If it was that easy,
I'd get you to do it.

313
00:22:37,320 --> 00:22:40,080
But how did you get your wrist out
without breaking it?

314
00:22:40,160 --> 00:22:41,640
You asked. I did. Problem?

315
00:22:41,720 --> 00:22:42,800
(CHUCKLING)

316
00:22:43,600 --> 00:22:45,080
You just changed the future.

317
00:22:45,160 --> 00:22:47,960
It's called marriage, honey.
Now, hush. I'm working.

318
00:22:48,080 --> 00:22:49,120
DOCTOR: She's good, eh?

319
00:22:49,200 --> 00:22:51,720
Oh! Have you noticed?
Really, really good.

320
00:22:51,800 --> 00:22:54,080
Ah. Wherever it is,
it's within a few blocks.

321
00:22:54,160 --> 00:22:55,760
There's a car out front.
Shall we steal it?

322
00:22:55,880 --> 00:22:57,120
Show me!

323
00:22:57,280 --> 00:22:58,520
(GROANS)

324
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:03,360
(SHUDDERING)

325
00:23:20,120 --> 00:23:21,920
(LIFT BELL DINGS)

326
00:23:23,960 --> 00:23:28,440
Okay. Um, when all those numbers
on both units go to zero,

327
00:23:28,520 --> 00:23:29,800
that's when we've got a lock, okay?

328
00:23:31,160 --> 00:23:33,840
-That's how we find Rory.
-Got it.

329
00:23:35,480 --> 00:23:37,280
DOCTOR: Why did you lie to me?

330
00:23:41,520 --> 00:23:44,080
When one's in love with an ageless god

331
00:23:44,160 --> 00:23:47,960
who insists on the face
of a 12-year-old,

332
00:23:49,040 --> 00:23:51,560
one does one's best to hide the damage.

333
00:23:53,800 --> 00:23:56,600
-(SOFTLY) It must hurt. Come here.
-Yes.

334
00:23:58,760 --> 00:24:00,600
The wrist is pretty bad, too.

335
00:24:12,760 --> 00:24:14,440
(EXCLAIMS) No. No, no.

336
00:24:15,360 --> 00:24:17,880
Stop that. Stop that. Stop it!

337
00:24:20,680 --> 00:24:22,120
There you go.

338
00:24:23,280 --> 00:24:24,640
How's that?

339
00:24:26,280 --> 00:24:27,480
Well...

340
00:24:27,880 --> 00:24:29,440
Let's see, shall we?

341
00:24:30,560 --> 00:24:33,880
That was a stupid
waste of regeneration energy.

342
00:24:33,960 --> 00:24:36,560
Nothing is gained
by you being a sentimental idiot!

343
00:24:36,800 --> 00:24:38,600
-River!
-No! You embarrass me.

344
00:24:38,680 --> 00:24:39,840
River!

345
00:24:44,520 --> 00:24:47,280
Tell you what.
Stick to the science part.

346
00:24:51,760 --> 00:24:53,240
(DOOR CLOSING)

347
00:24:56,120 --> 00:24:59,040
Okay. Why did you lie?

348
00:25:00,720 --> 00:25:02,920
Never let him see the damage.

349
00:25:08,480 --> 00:25:12,400
And never ever let him see you age.

350
00:25:13,960 --> 00:25:15,920
He doesn't like endings.

351
00:25:18,160 --> 00:25:19,360
(DEVICE BEEPING)

352
00:25:20,680 --> 00:25:22,160
There you are.

353
00:25:23,920 --> 00:25:26,160
Got it!
He's in a place called Winter Quay.

354
00:25:26,240 --> 00:25:28,160
The car. Yes, let's go.

355
00:25:45,840 --> 00:25:47,880
(GROANING)

356
00:26:07,720 --> 00:26:09,360
(EXCLAIMS SOFTLY)

357
00:26:45,640 --> 00:26:47,320
(TYRES SCREECHING)

358
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:51,440
RIVER: Why would they send him here?

359
00:26:51,880 --> 00:26:54,200
Why not zap him back in time
like they normally do?

360
00:26:54,280 --> 00:26:56,440
We'll know that
when we know what this place is.

361
00:26:56,640 --> 00:26:58,120
(DEVICE BEEPING RAPIDLY)

362
00:26:58,200 --> 00:26:59,840
AMY: Winter Quay.

363
00:27:09,800 --> 00:27:11,680
-Rory?
-RIVER: He's close.

364
00:27:11,880 --> 00:27:12,920
Rory!

365
00:27:16,280 --> 00:27:17,640
-Rory.
-Amy.

366
00:27:18,360 --> 00:27:19,800
(DEVICE BEEPING RAPIDLY)

367
00:27:20,960 --> 00:27:22,360
Doctor.

368
00:27:22,440 --> 00:27:23,880
Look at this.

369
00:27:25,560 --> 00:27:26,600
Why's it smiling?

370
00:27:31,520 --> 00:27:32,880
Amy. Rory!

371
00:27:32,960 --> 00:27:35,640
Get out of here.
Don't look at anything. Don't touch...

372
00:27:35,720 --> 00:27:36,960
Who's that?

373
00:27:37,960 --> 00:27:39,200
(GROANS)

374
00:27:39,320 --> 00:27:40,600
Amy.

375
00:27:41,440 --> 00:27:43,360
Amy, please...

376
00:27:47,680 --> 00:27:48,920
(COUGHING)

377
00:27:52,800 --> 00:27:53,880
Amy.

378
00:27:55,440 --> 00:27:56,720
Please.

379
00:27:58,240 --> 00:27:59,320
Please.

380
00:28:07,520 --> 00:28:08,640
Rory?

381
00:28:16,160 --> 00:28:17,440
He's here.

382
00:28:25,640 --> 00:28:26,880
Amy.

383
00:28:38,040 --> 00:28:40,800
Would someone please tell me
what is going on?

384
00:28:47,960 --> 00:28:49,560
I'm sorry, Rory.

385
00:28:51,080 --> 00:28:52,640
But you just died.

386
00:29:07,960 --> 00:29:09,280
DOCTOR: This place is policed by Angels.

387
00:29:09,360 --> 00:29:11,800
Every time you try to escape,
you get zapped back in time.

388
00:29:11,960 --> 00:29:14,680
So, this place belongs to the Angels?
They built it?

389
00:29:14,760 --> 00:29:17,560
Displacing someone back in time
creates time energy.

390
00:29:17,640 --> 00:29:20,280
And that is what the Angels feed on.

391
00:29:20,760 --> 00:29:23,640
But normally, it's a one-off,
a hit-and-run.

392
00:29:24,280 --> 00:29:26,240
If they could keep hold
of their victims,

393
00:29:26,320 --> 00:29:29,680
feed off their time energy
over and over again...

394
00:29:31,920 --> 00:29:35,120
This place is a farm. A battery farm.

395
00:29:36,440 --> 00:29:37,560
How many Angels in New York?

396
00:29:37,640 --> 00:29:39,440
It's like they've taken over
every statue in the city.

397
00:29:39,880 --> 00:29:41,640
Yeah, the Angels take Manhattan
because they can.

398
00:29:41,720 --> 00:29:43,280
Because they've never had
a food source like this one.

399
00:29:43,360 --> 00:29:44,840
The city that never sleeps.

400
00:29:44,920 --> 00:29:47,200
(CRASHING FOOTSTEPS IN DISTANCE)

401
00:29:47,960 --> 00:29:49,440
What was that?

402
00:29:52,280 --> 00:29:53,320
I don't know.

403
00:29:54,960 --> 00:29:57,120
But I think they're coming for you.

404
00:29:58,480 --> 00:30:00,240
What does that mean?

405
00:30:00,720 --> 00:30:01,800
What is going to happen to me?

406
00:30:02,200 --> 00:30:03,320
What is physically going to happen?

407
00:30:04,560 --> 00:30:06,760
The Angels will come for you.

408
00:30:06,840 --> 00:30:08,760
They'll zap you back in time
to this very spot,

409
00:30:08,840 --> 00:30:10,040
30, 40 years ago.

410
00:30:11,080 --> 00:30:15,000
And you will live out
the rest of your life in that room

411
00:30:16,120 --> 00:30:18,160
until you die in that bed.

412
00:30:21,160 --> 00:30:22,360
And will Amy be there?

413
00:30:23,160 --> 00:30:25,680
-No.
-How do you know?

414
00:30:25,760 --> 00:30:28,360
Because he was so pleased
to see you again.

415
00:30:32,480 --> 00:30:33,600
Okay.

416
00:30:33,800 --> 00:30:36,120
Well, they haven't taken me yet.

417
00:30:36,440 --> 00:30:39,680
What if I just run?
What if I just get the hell out of here?

418
00:30:39,760 --> 00:30:42,800
-Then that never happens.
-It already happened, Rory.

419
00:30:42,880 --> 00:30:45,080
You've just witnessed your own future.

420
00:30:45,880 --> 00:30:47,280
Doctor, he's right.

421
00:30:47,360 --> 00:30:48,400
No, he isn't.

422
00:30:48,480 --> 00:30:50,560
If Rory got out,
it would create a paradox.

423
00:30:50,640 --> 00:30:51,720
(CRASHING CONTINUES)

424
00:30:51,800 --> 00:30:54,440
-What is that?
-This is the Angels' food source.

425
00:30:54,520 --> 00:30:57,200
The paradox poisons the well.
It could kill them all.

426
00:30:57,640 --> 00:31:00,240
Oh, this whole place
would literally un-happen.

427
00:31:00,320 --> 00:31:03,160
It would be almost impossible.

428
00:31:03,240 --> 00:31:04,440
Loving the "almost".

429
00:31:04,520 --> 00:31:09,520
But to create a paradox like that
takes almost unimaginable power.

430
00:31:09,600 --> 00:31:12,320
What have we got, hey? Tell me.
Come on. What?

431
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:18,840
I won't let them take him.
That's what we got.

432
00:31:19,200 --> 00:31:21,480
(CRASHING FOOTSTEPS GETTING CLOSER)

433
00:31:22,920 --> 00:31:24,760
Whatever that thing is,
it is getting closer.

434
00:31:24,840 --> 00:31:25,920
DOCTOR: Rory.

435
00:31:26,320 --> 00:31:30,200
Even if you got out, you'd have to
keep running for the rest of your life.

436
00:31:30,280 --> 00:31:32,400
They would be chasing you forever.

437
00:31:32,480 --> 00:31:34,720
Well, then, better get started.

438
00:31:36,560 --> 00:31:37,920
Husband, run!

439
00:31:44,120 --> 00:31:47,800
-River, I'm not sure this can work.
-Husband, shut up.

440
00:31:53,560 --> 00:31:55,280
(DOCTOR EXCLAIMS)

441
00:31:58,960 --> 00:32:00,240
-Up. \ hat good's up -W

442
00:32:00,320 --> 00:32:01,640
Better than down.

443
00:32:03,240 --> 00:32:05,320
-We can't keep doing this.
-Any ideas?

444
00:32:05,400 --> 00:32:06,760
Yeah, the usual.

445
00:32:06,840 --> 00:32:08,000
Run!

446
00:32:27,200 --> 00:32:29,440
Um, okay. Fire escape.

447
00:32:30,680 --> 00:32:33,200
RORY: I always wanted to visit
the Statue of Liberty.

448
00:32:33,680 --> 00:32:35,480
I guess she got impatient.

449
00:32:40,040 --> 00:32:41,440
What? What is it? What?

450
00:32:41,520 --> 00:32:42,760
Just keep your eyes on that.

451
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:45,000
-Oh, God.
-Is there a way down?

452
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:47,320
RORY: Uh...

453
00:32:48,040 --> 00:32:50,080
No. But there's a way out.

454
00:32:52,360 --> 00:32:54,080
What are you doing?

455
00:32:54,960 --> 00:32:56,240
RORY: Oh.

456
00:32:57,040 --> 00:32:59,280
AMY: Rory, what are you doing?

457
00:33:01,800 --> 00:33:02,920
Rory?

458
00:33:03,480 --> 00:33:05,320
-Stop it. You'll die.
-Yeah. Twice.

459
00:33:05,880 --> 00:33:07,840
In the same building, on the same night.

460
00:33:07,920 --> 00:33:08,960
Who else could do that?

461
00:33:09,320 --> 00:33:10,400
Just come down, please.

462
00:33:10,480 --> 00:33:12,040
This is the right thing to do.

463
00:33:12,800 --> 00:33:15,880
This will work.
If I die now, it's a paradox, right?

464
00:33:15,960 --> 00:33:17,400
The paradox killed the Angels.

465
00:33:17,480 --> 00:33:19,160
Tell me I'm wrong.

466
00:33:19,520 --> 00:33:22,320
Go on.
Please, because I am really scared.

467
00:33:26,480 --> 00:33:27,640
Great.

468
00:33:29,040 --> 00:33:30,600
It's the one time you can't manage it.

469
00:33:32,320 --> 00:33:33,640
(BOTH GASP)

470
00:33:34,240 --> 00:33:35,840
Oh, God.

471
00:33:40,320 --> 00:33:41,400
Amy.

472
00:33:42,320 --> 00:33:45,800
I'm going to...need a little help here.

473
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:49,840
-No. Just stop it.
-No, just think it through.

474
00:33:49,920 --> 00:33:51,720
This will work.
This will kill the Angels.

475
00:33:51,800 --> 00:33:54,080
-It will kill you, too.
-Will it?

476
00:33:54,160 --> 00:33:56,120
River said that this place would be
erased from time, never exist.

477
00:33:56,200 --> 00:33:58,280
But if this place never existed,
what did I fall off?

478
00:33:58,360 --> 00:33:59,600
You think you'll just come back to life?

479
00:33:59,680 --> 00:34:00,840
-When don't I?
-Rory.

480
00:34:00,920 --> 00:34:03,040
And anyway, what else is there?

481
00:34:03,120 --> 00:34:05,400
Die of old age downstairs,
never seeing you again?

482
00:34:06,400 --> 00:34:11,240
Amy, please,
if you love me, then trust me

483
00:34:11,640 --> 00:34:12,920
and push.

484
00:34:17,280 --> 00:34:18,520
-I can't.
-You have to!

485
00:34:18,600 --> 00:34:20,200
Could you?

486
00:34:20,280 --> 00:34:22,400
If it was me, could you do it?

487
00:34:26,760 --> 00:34:28,120
To save you,

488
00:34:29,320 --> 00:34:30,680
I could do anything.

489
00:34:54,160 --> 00:34:55,360
Prove it.

490
00:34:55,440 --> 00:34:58,560
-No, I can't take you, too.
-You said we'd come back to life.

491
00:35:00,640 --> 00:35:01,880
Money where your mouth is time.

492
00:35:01,960 --> 00:35:04,360
-Amy, pl...
-Shut up.

493
00:35:05,880 --> 00:35:07,160
Together

494
00:35:08,200 --> 00:35:09,680
or not at all.

495
00:35:11,120 --> 00:35:12,560
What the hell are you doing?

496
00:35:12,640 --> 00:35:14,000
AMY: Changing the future.

497
00:35:17,920 --> 00:35:19,720
It's called marriage.

498
00:35:22,360 --> 00:35:23,560
Amy!

499
00:35:24,400 --> 00:35:25,720
Amy!

500
00:35:28,720 --> 00:35:29,800
Amy!

501
00:35:47,160 --> 00:35:48,360
Doctor!

502
00:35:52,840 --> 00:35:54,480
What's happening?

503
00:35:55,720 --> 00:35:57,760
The paradox. It's working.

504
00:35:58,360 --> 00:36:00,240
The paradox is working!

505
00:36:05,480 --> 00:36:07,160
(BIRDS TWITTERING)

506
00:36:18,120 --> 00:36:19,480
(BOTH GASP)

507
00:36:20,080 --> 00:36:22,120
-Where are we?
-Back where we started.

508
00:36:22,560 --> 00:36:24,640
You collapsed the timeline.
The paradox worked.

509
00:36:24,720 --> 00:36:26,240
We all pinged back where we belong.

510
00:36:26,320 --> 00:36:27,800
What? In a graveyard?

511
00:36:27,880 --> 00:36:29,800
This happened last time.
Why always here?

512
00:36:29,880 --> 00:36:31,880
Does it matter? We got lucky.

513
00:36:31,960 --> 00:36:33,520
We could have blown New York
off the planet.

514
00:36:33,600 --> 00:36:34,760
I can't ever take
the Tardis back, though,

515
00:36:34,840 --> 00:36:37,240
the timelines are too scrambled.

516
00:36:37,440 --> 00:36:40,400
(SIGHS IN RELIEF)
I could have lost you both.

517
00:36:41,440 --> 00:36:43,960
Don't ever do that again.

518
00:36:44,040 --> 00:36:45,800
RORY: What did... What did we do?

519
00:36:45,880 --> 00:36:47,360
We fixed it. We solved the problem.

520
00:36:48,080 --> 00:36:50,040
I was talking to myself.

521
00:36:50,840 --> 00:36:52,440
(BOTH LAUGHING)

522
00:36:52,960 --> 00:36:54,240
(EXHALES)

523
00:36:56,040 --> 00:36:58,480
It could do with a repaint.

524
00:36:58,720 --> 00:37:02,520
-I've been busy.
-Does the bulb on top need changing?

525
00:37:02,880 --> 00:37:07,080
-I just changed it.
-So, Rory and Amy, then.

526
00:37:07,240 --> 00:37:09,080
Yes, I know. I know.

527
00:37:09,160 --> 00:37:10,760
I'm just saying.

528
00:37:10,960 --> 00:37:13,760
They're going to get terribly bored
hanging round here all day.

529
00:37:13,840 --> 00:37:15,480
-Doctor.
-Ha!

530
00:37:15,800 --> 00:37:17,520
Look, next time,
can we just go to the pub?

531
00:37:17,840 --> 00:37:19,800
DOCTOR:
I want to go to the pub right now.

532
00:37:19,880 --> 00:37:22,160
Aren't there video games there?
I love video games.

533
00:37:22,920 --> 00:37:24,240
Right. Family outing, then.

534
00:37:31,760 --> 00:37:32,840
Amy.

535
00:37:33,040 --> 00:37:34,600
-Come and see this.
-What?

536
00:37:34,960 --> 00:37:38,400
There's a gravestone here
for someone with the same name as me.

537
00:37:38,520 --> 00:37:39,640
What?

538
00:37:43,160 --> 00:37:44,360
Doctor?

539
00:37:45,720 --> 00:37:46,760
Ah.

540
00:37:46,840 --> 00:37:48,760
Where the hell did that come from?

541
00:37:48,840 --> 00:37:52,520
It's a survivor.
Very weak, but keep your eyes on it.

542
00:37:52,600 --> 00:37:53,640
Where's Rory?

543
00:38:05,120 --> 00:38:06,440
I'm sorry.

544
00:38:08,040 --> 00:38:11,720
Amelia, I'm so, so sorry.

545
00:38:13,760 --> 00:38:16,600
No. No, we can just go and get him
in the Tardis.

546
00:38:16,920 --> 00:38:18,040
One more paradox.

547
00:38:18,120 --> 00:38:19,160
Would rip New York apart.

548
00:38:19,240 --> 00:38:22,160
-That's not true. I don't believe you.
-Mother, it's true.

549
00:38:27,880 --> 00:38:29,520
Amy, what are you doing?

550
00:38:29,600 --> 00:38:30,640
That gravestone, Rory's,

551
00:38:30,720 --> 00:38:32,560
there's room for one more name,
isn't there?

552
00:38:32,640 --> 00:38:34,640
What are you talking about?
Back away from the angel.

553
00:38:34,720 --> 00:38:36,440
Come back to the Tardis.
We'll figure something out.

554
00:38:36,520 --> 00:38:39,120
The angel, would it send me back
to the same time, to him?

555
00:38:39,200 --> 00:38:40,960
I don't know. Nobody knows.

556
00:38:41,880 --> 00:38:43,920
-But it's my best shot, yeah?
-No!

557
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:46,200
Doctor, shut up! Yes. Yes, it is.

558
00:38:46,280 --> 00:38:47,640
-Amy...
-Well, then.

559
00:38:48,440 --> 00:38:50,800
-I just have to blink, right?
-No!

560
00:38:50,880 --> 00:38:52,640
It will be fine. I know it will.

561
00:38:52,720 --> 00:38:55,720
I'LL be with him. Like I should be.

562
00:38:55,800 --> 00:38:57,280
Me and Rory together.

563
00:39:00,720 --> 00:39:01,800
Melody?

564
00:39:02,080 --> 00:39:03,400
Stop it! Just, just stop it!

565
00:39:10,960 --> 00:39:12,680
You look after him.

566
00:39:12,880 --> 00:39:15,760
And you be a good girl
and you look after him.

567
00:39:15,840 --> 00:39:18,440
DOCTOR: You are creating fixed time.

568
00:39:19,120 --> 00:39:21,160
I will never be able to see you again.

569
00:39:21,240 --> 00:39:23,760
I will be fine. I'll be with him.

570
00:39:23,920 --> 00:39:25,800
DOCTOR: Amy, please.

571
00:39:26,840 --> 00:39:30,040
Just come back into the Tardis.

572
00:39:30,720 --> 00:39:32,560
Come on, Pond, please.

573
00:39:37,920 --> 00:39:39,320
Raggedy Man,

574
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:42,280
goodbye.

575
00:39:47,960 --> 00:39:49,320
DOCTOR: No!

576
00:40:12,680 --> 00:40:14,120
(WHOOSHING)

577
00:40:15,600 --> 00:40:17,240
(SCREEN HUMS)

578
00:40:17,760 --> 00:40:19,240
(RIVER TYPING)

579
00:40:21,320 --> 00:40:22,480
River.

580
00:40:25,440 --> 00:40:27,360
They were your parents.

581
00:40:28,880 --> 00:40:31,520
Sorry. I didn't even think.

582
00:40:33,480 --> 00:40:34,680
It doesn't matter.

583
00:40:35,880 --> 00:40:39,200
-Of course it matters.
-What matters is this, Doctor.

584
00:40:40,480 --> 00:40:41,880
Don't travel alone.

585
00:40:45,600 --> 00:40:47,280
Travel with me, then.

586
00:40:47,760 --> 00:40:49,440
(TARDIS STARTS UP)

587
00:40:50,720 --> 00:40:53,000
Whenever and wherever you want.

588
00:40:56,200 --> 00:40:57,880
But not all the time.

589
00:40:57,960 --> 00:41:01,080
One psychopath per Tardis,
don't you think?

590
00:41:02,560 --> 00:41:04,160
(TARDIS HUMMING)

591
00:41:08,200 --> 00:41:09,320
Okay.

592
00:41:09,680 --> 00:41:11,680
This book I've got to write,
Melody Malone.

593
00:41:11,880 --> 00:41:13,920
I presume I send it to Amy
to get it published?

594
00:41:14,200 --> 00:41:15,480
Yes. Yes.

595
00:41:19,840 --> 00:41:21,720
I'LL tell her to write an afterword.

596
00:41:24,800 --> 00:41:26,040
For you.

597
00:41:31,880 --> 00:41:33,960
Maybe you'll listen to her.

598
00:41:41,960 --> 00:41:43,120
The last page!

599
00:42:01,840 --> 00:42:04,320
AMY: "Afterword by Amelia Williams.

600
00:42:04,720 --> 00:42:06,480
"Hello, old friend.

601
00:42:06,560 --> 00:42:09,480
"And here we are. You and me.

602
00:42:09,560 --> 00:42:10,800
"On the last page.

603
00:42:12,160 --> 00:42:15,560
"By the time you read these words,
Rory and I will be long gone.

604
00:42:16,200 --> 00:42:19,360
"So know that we lived well
and were very happy.

605
00:42:20,320 --> 00:42:23,800
"And above all else,
know that we will love you always.

606
00:42:26,800 --> 00:42:29,480
"Sometimes I do worry about you, though.

607
00:42:29,600 --> 00:42:31,440
"I think once we're gone,

608
00:42:31,520 --> 00:42:33,840
"you won't be coming back here
for a while

609
00:42:33,920 --> 00:42:37,880
"and you might be alone,
which you should never be.

610
00:42:38,080 --> 00:42:40,040
"Don't be alone, Doctor.

611
00:42:41,200 --> 00:42:43,440
"And do one more thing for me.

612
00:42:44,680 --> 00:42:47,520
"There's a little girl
waiting in a garden.

613
00:42:47,760 --> 00:42:51,760
"She's going to wait a long while,
so she's going to need a lot of hope.

614
00:42:52,360 --> 00:42:54,560
"Go to her, tell her a story.

615
00:42:55,200 --> 00:42:57,120
"Tell her that if she's patient,

616
00:42:57,200 --> 00:43:00,200
“the days are coming
that she'll never forget.

617
00:43:00,800 --> 00:43:03,760
"Tell her she'll go to sea
and fight pirates.

618
00:43:04,200 --> 00:43:05,560
"She'll fall in love with a man

619
00:43:05,640 --> 00:43:08,440
"who'll wait 2,000 years
to keep her safe.

620
00:43:09,200 --> 00:43:13,120
"Tell her she'll give hope
to the greatest painter who ever lived

621
00:43:13,200 --> 00:43:15,320
"and save a whale in outer space.

622
00:43:17,320 --> 00:43:21,440
"Tell her this is the story
of Amelia Pond

623
00:43:23,200 --> 00:43:25,240
"and this is how it ends."

624
00:43:25,320 --> 00:43:27,360
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

